{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647211"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:41:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18231"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.75,0.04,0.08,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10945"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75810"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10945"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25443"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75810"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of black discolouration on the skin of her fingers on the left hand. She reports that it appeared suddenly and are not painful. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and hypertension. Her regular medications include Warfarin and Amlodipine. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. The left hand shows several small, black, non-tender, poorly demarcated black discolouration on the fingertips. The radial and ulnar pulses are weakly palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cellulitis","Arterial insufficiency","Melanoma","Venous congestion","Fungal infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sudden appearance of black discolouration on the skin, or gangrene, in the context of weak pulses, suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Earterial insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition can result from emboli or thrombosis, leading to tissue ischaemia and necrosis, which presents as black or necrotic areas on the skin. The patient\u0027s history of atrial fibrillation increases the risk of embolic events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with redness, warmth, and tenderness, rather than gangrene. It is an infection of the skin and subcutaneous tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of skin cancer that can present as a pigmented lesion, but it usually develops over a longer period and is not associated with asudden onset or weak pulses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous congestion\u003C/strong\u003E would more likely cause swelling and a bluish discoloration rather than gangrene. It is due to impaired venous return, not arterial issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes scaling, redness, and itching. It is unlikely to present with sudden onset or weak pulses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of gangrene indicates ischaemia from arterial insufficiency, often due to emboli or thrombosis.","Arterial insufficiency can lead to tissue ischemia and necrosis, presenting as black or necrotic areas on the skin.","Prompt recognition and management of arterial insufficiency are crucial to prevent further tissue damage."],"references":["Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York.","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing.","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers.","Blessley-Redgrave N, Bowerman F, Dafydd H, Hemington-Gorse S, Boyce D. Malignant melanoma in the hand: current evidence and recommendations. J Hand Surg Eur Vol. 2024 Jul;49(7):831-842. doi: 10.1177/17531934241245028. Epub 2024 Apr 25. PMID: 38663875."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T15:29:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T15:29:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10945"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75810"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{